      "SummaryText": "Risk Management Plan - Executive Summary\r\n\r\nFacility:\tMFA Anhydrous Ammonia Plant\r\nLocation:\t3501 South Hwy 61, Perryville, Mo. 63775\r\nContact: \tBrian Myers\r\nPhone: \t\t573-547-2547 \r\n\r\n1. The Facility Policy\r\n\r\nMFA Incorporated and the employees of the MFA Anhydrous Plant in Perryville are committed to the prevention of any accidental release of anhydrous ammonia. If an accidental release should occur, the facility is prepared to work with the Southeast Missouri LEPC, and other authorities, to mitigate any release and minimize the impact of the release to people and the environment.\r\n\r\n2. Facility Information\r\n\r\nThe primary activity at the facility is the receiving, storage and distribution of anhydrous ammonia for direct application as a crop nutrient. The maximum quantity handled would be the unloading of a transport delivery truck holding approximately 50,000 pounds.\r\n\r\n\r\n3. The Accidental Release Prevention Program.\r\n\r\nThe facility has implemented the provisions of Safety Requirements for the Storage and Handling of Anhydrous Ammonia, K-61.1, 1999, published by The American National Standards Institute, Inc., The Missouri Anhydrous Ammonia regulations and the standards of the U.S. Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA), 29 CFR 1910.111, Storage and handling of Anhydrous Ammonia. The facility will work to meet new codes as time and budgets allow.\r\n\r\n4. The Five-year Accident History\r\n\r\nThere have been no accidental releases of anhydrous ammonia in the past five years that: have caused any deaths, injuries, or significant property damage at the facility; nor to our knowledge, have resulted in offsite deaths, injuries, evacuations, sheltering in place, property damage, or environmental damage.\r\n\r\n\r\n5. The Emergency Response Program.\r\n\r\n\tThe facility has;\r\n\r\n\t\ta. a written emergency action plan, in accordance with OSHA Standard, 29 CFR 1910.38;\r\n\r\n\t\tb. provided State and Local authorities with the emergency planning and community right-to-"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000056604,
      "SummaryText": "know information as required under SARA Title III (EPCRA);\r\n\r\n\t\tc. employees will not respond to any releases other than to activate an emergency shut-off valve \r\n\t\t   while evacuating the facility if it is safe for them to do so. Local emergency responders will be \r\n\t\t   notified to control any release.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n6. Planned changes to improve safety.\r\n\r\nSafety improvement is an on-going process at the facility. Periodic evaluations are performed to assess the maintenance of safe conditions. Currently the facility is evaluating the requirements of CGA 2.1, 2014 and Process Management of Highly Hazardous Chemicals and will make the required upgrades needed.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\t4/1/16"
    }
